msItem.title: Guta lag
msItem.incipit: Thitta ier fyrst vphoff i laghum warom
msItem.colophon: Exaratum Anno 1587. 14. Calend: Iunij, per Dauidem Bilefeld Ecclesiasten Barlingboënsem ac præpositum Borealis TERTIANÆ. iuxta Tenorem Veteris Exemplaris Anno MCD.LXX: Scripti:

foliation.p: There is foliation by the main scribe.

collation.signatures: There are quire signatures on fols. 7, 15, 23, 31, 39, 48, 56.
collation.catchwords: There are catchwords on every page.

condition.p: The manuscript is in good condition.
Small holes can be found in some of the leaves, e.g. fols. 23, 37, 38.
Some pages have been reinforced near the spine, e.g. 13, 14.

layout.p: The manuscript is written in one column with 19 to 22 lines per page.
The dimensions of the written area are ca. 135 115

decoDesc.decoNote: There are enlarged initials of 2-4 lines, often highlighted with red.

additions.p: There are additions added by the main scribe on fols. 1bisv, 7r, 7v, 9r, 10r, 11v, 12r, 21r, 21v, 22v, 25r, 25v, 36r, 37r, 37v, 41r, 45r, 46v, 54v.

binding.p: Bound in vellum from before 1728. The binding measures 209 171 17

accMat.p: There is an AM-slip pasted onto 1r. Árni Magnússon has written: Hæc ex LL Gotlandicis provincialibus penes Janum Rosæncranzium, habentibus capita 82; descriptis 1587 ex vetusto exemplari scripto 1470, quod ex pura lingvâ Norvegicâ depravatum esse clare patet, Titulus horam legum est Guthalag.

origin.p: The manuscript was written on 19 May 1587 on Gotland (part of the Danish kingdom until 1645) by David Hansen Bilefeld, a priest from Jutland.

provenance.p: The manuscript belonged to Jens Rosenkrantz and was likely bought from his estate auction.
at some point the manuscript was lent to Otto Sperling the Younger, who copied it (Copenhagen, Royal Library, GKS 3363 4to).

list.item: Digital photographs of the entire manuscript taken in 2016.
